WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.780
All right, the third in our trifecta is a somewhat different approach in mRNA-based

00:00:05.780 --> 00:00:09.140
generation of a tri-specific. This is Dr. Rodriguez.

00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:18.080
So not necessarily a tri-specific, a quad-specific. Yeah, great. So we're going to

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:24.320
shift gears a little bit, and I don't have any data to show, so don't worry about that,

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:29.440
or don't feel disappointed. What I want to do is teach and learn at the same time,

00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:37.720
because I had to sit down and read a lot about mRNA and nanolipids. So what I want to do is go

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:45.500
over that and then this mRNA agent. So in our body, we have the DNA that is then transcribed

00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:51.780
to messenger RNA, which the ribosomes then transform that into proteins. And in our body

00:00:51.780 --> 00:00:57.020
and in myeloma, we're making antibodies, right? So with the bispecifics and the tri-specifics,

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:05.780
the lab or ex vivo, these antibodies. Now with mRNA, now that we have all this experience with

00:01:05.780 --> 00:01:15.000
the COVID vaccines, and surprisingly, mRNA has been actually used and studied since the 1960s,

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:19.360
but it didn't really gain a lot of momentum until now that we're in the COVID world.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:27.940
So how can we actually do mRNA therapy that helps create antibodies in the body?

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:34.800
So for that, we need lipid nanoparticles. And in order to make an mRNA lipid nanoparticle,

00:01:35.180 --> 00:01:42.400
you first need to prepare the linearized DNA template. And then you're going to have to

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:49.320
transcribe the mRNA in vitro, and you have to purify it. And then once you have it purified,

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:55.300
you're going to do a rapid mixing. So what you want to do, if you introduce RNA alone into a body,

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.620
the body's going to dissolve the RNA, and it's not going to last in the body long.

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:08.460
So we need to cover it with a lipid layer so that that gives the RNA a longer half-life.

00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:14.160
So the way to do that is by what's called a rapid mixing. So you have an aqueous phase,

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:19.660
which is the RNA, which is negatively charged. And then you have an organic phase, which is

00:02:19.660 --> 00:02:26.080
positively charged. This organic phase is the lipids. And you actually do a rapid mixing. You

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:27.500
throw both of them at the same time. And then you have a rapid mixing. And then you have a rapid

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:34.680
at the same time rapidly. And as a consequence, the lipids organize around the mRNA and make these

00:02:34.680 --> 00:02:40.540
capsule. So the core layer, which are the two small circles that you see there, are protecting

00:02:40.540 --> 00:02:45.860
the messenger RNA. And then you have an outer layer that's the one that's going to help

00:02:45.860 --> 00:02:51.820
with membrane fusions with cells and to increase the half-life of these

00:02:51.820 --> 00:02:57.480
nanolipids. So a nanolipid is going to contain the ionizable catonic lipids,

00:02:57.500 --> 00:03:02.380
which are the ones that are going to bind to the mRNA. It's going to have the phospholipids

00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:07.780
that are going to help with it permeating into membranes and moving across the body.

00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:12.500
It's going to have the pegylated lipids, which are going to give it a longer half-life.

00:03:13.100 --> 00:03:17.440
And it's going to have the cholesterol lipids, which are going to give it the structure.

00:03:18.020 --> 00:03:22.200
And depending on how much cholesterol you put is how big that nanolipid is going to be

00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:26.540
and how easily it's going to move in the body from one place to another.

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:30.260
And it's going to inflate the cargo, which is in this case, the mRNA.

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:41.620
So with Moderna, we have a first-in-human study using the studies mRNA-2808, and what it's doing

00:03:41.620 --> 00:03:48.500
is that it's developing lipid nanoparticles with four mRNAs. And these four mRNAs are going to

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:54.620
contain three, so three of these mRNAs are going to contain the information to be able to generate

00:03:54.620 --> 00:04:01.380
antibodies that are going to target CD3 on the T-cell and are going to target either BCMA,

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:09.840
GPRC5D, or FCRH5. So that is going to give us like a triple target for the myeloma,

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:13.320
and it's at the same time going to bind to the T-cell that's CD3.

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:19.660
This is administered intravenously, and the reason why intravenously is the route chosen is

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:24.600
if you give it intravenously, it's mainly going to concentrate in the liver and in the spleen,

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:30.180
thirdly in the lymph nodes, and then in those cells, the macrophages of the spleen mainly,

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:36.880
then that macrophage is going to use that mRNA to generate these antibodies in the liver.

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:43.340
But the mRNA is not going to integrate into the DNA, so we're not really causing any changes in

00:04:43.340 --> 00:04:50.080
the human genome, like other therapies in benign heme where we're actually doing

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:54.540
changes in genetic alteration. And then,

00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:59.980
once these cells are producing these antibodies, they're going to secrete these

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:08.640
bispecific T-cell engagers, targeting BCMA, GPRC5D, and FCRH5. So here we see how the structure

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:14.580
of those antibodies and the concept of the mechanism of how it works. And the key thing

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:18.820
is, okay, why are we doing mRNA? I mean, we already have the bispecifics, and we have the

00:05:18.820 --> 00:05:24.220
trispecifics, and we already know how to make these antibodies ex vivo. Why go through the

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:31.400
process of doing an mRNA? So there's a few things. One is that with the mRNA, you can actually

00:05:31.400 --> 00:05:40.100
deliver multiple targets at once. Instead of having to administer TEC and TAL, or having to

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:46.840
do a trispecific and combine it with another agent, here we have the ability to modify very easily

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:52.580
the number of different mRNAs that we're going to introduce into this nanolipid, and then deliver

00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:54.180
three different agents.

00:05:54.620 --> 00:06:03.040
At once. So we're delivering any of the BCMAs, whether it be TEC or LIMBO or ELRA, we're delivering

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:07.500
TALC, and we're delivering zivostimab, if we want to call it that way, just to make it simple,

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:15.700
all at once. We don't know the pharmacokinetics. We do not know the onset of action, because we

00:06:15.700 --> 00:06:19.320
first need to generate these antibodies, and then that's going to determine

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:24.620
what the CRS pattern and the timing of the CRS is going to be. And the regulatory

00:06:24.620 --> 00:06:29.980
pathway is still less established. So we still have a lot to learn. But in preclinical models, with

00:06:31.420 --> 00:06:38.940
apes, mouse and mouse models, we are seeing a great signal of these production of these antibodies

00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:47.260
and the target in myeloma cells, when these animals are, in fact, are co-cultured with myeloma.

00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:54.620
So this first-in-human study is going to help us answer that question. And in summary, this mRNA is

00:06:54.620 --> 00:07:02.300
the first of its kind in terms of therapeutic agent in multiple myeloma. It's a novel modality

00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:06.780
that enables delivery of multi-agent targeting antibodies in one therapy.

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:13.020
It also has the potential to reduce antigen escape, because you're attacking the myeloma

00:07:13.020 --> 00:07:18.620
cell from different angles. And at the same time, it has the potential to simplify production

00:07:18.620 --> 00:07:24.620
and cost of antibody therapy, because these are easy to make. They're easy to modify and manipulate

00:07:24.620 --> 00:07:29.820
or change. And then we're going to wait for the results, hopefully by next year,

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:33.580
we'll have some data for you guys to show.
